Upon completion of this course, students will be able to

1. identify a research topic;
2. conduct a bibliographical search for relevant existing studies;
3. critically engage with existing scholarship

4. develop a suitable methodological approach to the material that will allow the student to answer a research question;
5. be able to draft a research proposal.

courses.course_syllabus:
Topics will include:

1. What is a research topic, and what is a research question;
2. Literature review;
3. Linguistic methodologies;
4. Historical methodologies;
5. Literary methodologies;
6. Sociological methodologies;
7. Cultural Studies methodologies;
8. Structure of a research proposal.

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

1. understand the characteristics of both the English and Chinese languages;
2. analyze critically the factors involved in the language of literature in general;
3. the ability to identify specifically the stylistic features, both linguistic and non-linguistic, of prose, fiction, drama, and poetry;
4. think critically about literary genres via the study of theories;
5. combine theories with practical translation of prose, fiction, drama, and poetry from Chinese into English; and

6. translate Chinese prose, fiction, drama, and poetry into English with a degree of competence expected of students majoring in translation.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. the stylistic features of the four genres: classical and modern prose, classical and modern fiction, traditional and modern drama, and classical and modern poetry;
2. linguistic and cultural differences involved in the translation of these genres;
3. translating Chinese prose;
4. translating Chinese fiction;
5. translating Chinese drama;
6. translating Chinese poetry.

courses.learning_outcomes:
1. Understand the HK legal system and legal provisions on interpreting service;
2. Understand the process of consecutive interpreting under a unified theoretical framework ;

3. Improve active listening and concentration skills, memory;
4. Grasp the basic skills and techniques of court interpreting from between Cantonese and English

5. Learn and apply legal terminology in interpreting;
6. Understand professional ethics of court interpreters.

7. Be able to critically assess court interpreting scenarios and appropriate interpreting tactics.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

1. understand the characteristics of both both the English and Chinese languages;
2. analyze critically the factors involved in the language of literature in general;
3. identify specifically the stylistic features, both linguistic and non-linguistic, of prose, fiction, drama, and poetry;
4. think critically about literary genres via the study of theories;
5. combine theories with practical the translation of prose, fiction, drama, and poetry into Chinese; and

6. translate English prose, fiction, drama, and poetry into Chinese with a degree of competence expected of students majoring in translation.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. basically understand the history of machine translation development;
2. systematically describe the different kinds of knowledge required for machine translation;
3. competently discuss the various approaches to machine translation; and

4. critically evaluate existing (online) machine translation systems.

With the completion of this course, students will have:

1. acquired the knowledge of a special topic in translation;
2. learned the skills of studying the literature in a specialized area of translation;
3. engaged in critical thinking

4. mastered the techniques of translating specialized texts or conducting research on specific subject matters related to the field of translation studies.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to

1. understand the concepts and terminologies used in arts writings;
2. appreciate various types of arts writings and evaluate related translations critically;
3. acquire appropriate skills and applying them critically for translating arts texts;
4. understand and observe how translation theories can be applied in this particular type of translation activity;
5. develop critical and creative thinking in the translation and critiquing process.

Upon completing the course, students will be able to

1. understand the practice of commercial translation in the Hong Kong market;
2. familiarize themselves with terminologies in, and stylistic features of bilingual business writings;
3. identify problems in the commercial translation practice critically; and

4. formulate effective translating strategies in dealing with such problems.

Upon completion of this course, students will

1. acquire the basic skills for analysing and translating texts for the media;
2. be able to reflect on the ideological issue concerning mass media translation, and the relation between language and ideology;
3. develop critical thinking and interpersonal communication skills through group work, presentations and class discussion.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. Defining the Mass Media and the nature of mass media communication;
2. Language and style: news reports, webpage, advertisements, etc.;
3. Analytical tools: Text-types and translation types; Critical Discourse Analysis;
4. Translation approaches and skills for different types of mass media texts.

